Class LinkedList<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • projects.pqueue.lists.LinkedList<T>
  • Type Parameters:

    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<T>, List<T>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DoublyLinkedList
    public class LinkedList<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements List<T>

    LinkedList is a simple (forwardly-linked) List. A linked list is the most common List out there. The main benefit compared to an array-based implementation is that it's a dynamic data structure which never has to expand its capacity to accommodate new elements. The main drawbacks (compared to an array-based implementation such as StaticArrayList) is that certain methods, such as accessing or deleting methods based on indices, are not that efficient.

    You should not edit this class! It is given to you as a resource for your project.

      • equals

        public boolean equals​(java.lang.Object other)
        Standard equals() method. Two LinearLists are equal if they contain the exact same elements at the same positions. Note that this equals() method allows for comparing different implementations of LinearLists, and potentially allowing them to be equal because they maintain the aforementioned contract! We are interested in ADT comparison, not 1-1 memory allocation comparison.
        Overrides:
        equals in class java.lang.Object
        Parameters:
        other - The Object reference to compare to
        Returns:
        true if the two objects are considered "equal", with equality defined above.
